aa(lp56
VI've always thought of myself as a caregiver \u2014
p57
aVmost physicians do \u2014
p58
aVand taking care of Paul deepened what that meant.
p59
aVWatching him reshape his identity during his illness,
p60
aVlearning to witness and accept his pain,
p61
aVtalking together through his choices \u2014
p62
aVthose experiences taught me
p63
aVthat resilience does not mean bouncing back to where you were before,
p64
aVor pretending that the hard stuff isn't hard.
p65
aVIt is so hard.
p66
aVIt's painful, messy stuff.
p67
aVBut it's the stuff.
