aa(lp99
VAs physicians,
p100
aVPaul and I were in a good position
p101
aVto understand and even accept his diagnosis.
p102
aVWe weren't angry about it,
p103
aVluckily,
p104
aVbecause we'd seen so many patients in devastating situations,
p105
aVand we knew that death is a part of life.
p106
aVBut it's one thing to know that;
p107
aVit was a very different experience
p108
aVto actually live with the sadness and uncertainty of a serious illness.
p109
aVHuge strides are being made against lung cancer,
p110
aVbut we knew that Paul likely had months to a few years left to live.
p111
aa(lp112
VDuring that time,
p113
aVPaul wrote about his transition from doctor to patient.
p114
aVHe talked about feeling like he was suddenly at a crossroads,
p115
aVand how he would have thought he'd be able to see the path,
p116
aVthat because he treated so many patients,
p117
aVmaybe he could follow in their footsteps.
p118
aVBut he was totally disoriented.
p119
aVRather than a path,
p120
aVPaul wrote,
p121
aV"I saw instead
p122
aVonly a harsh, vacant, gleaming white desert.
p123
aVAs if a sandstorm had erased all familiarity.
p124
aVI had to face my mortality
p125
aVand try to understand what made my life worth living,
p126
aVand I needed my oncologist's help to do so."
