aa(lp128
VThe clinicians taking care of Paul
p129
aVgave me an even deeper appreciation for my colleagues in health care.
p130
aVWe have a tough job.
p131
aVWe're responsible for helping patients have clarity around their prognoses
p132
aVand their treatment options,
p133
aVand that's never easy, but it's especially tough
p134
aVwhen you're dealing with potentially terminal illnesses like cancer.
p135
aVSome people don't want to know how long they have left,
p136
aVothers do.
p137
aVEither way, we never have those answers.
p138
aVSometimes we substitute hope
p139
aVby emphasizing the best-case scenario.
p140
aVIn a survey of physicians,
p141
aV55 percent said they painted a rosier picture
p142
aVthan their honest opinion
p143
aVwhen describing a patient's prognosis.
p144
aVIt's an instinct born out of kindness.
p145
aVBut researchers have found
p146
aVthat when people better understand the possible outcomes of an illness,
p147
aVthey have less anxiety,
p148
aVgreater ability to plan
p149
aVand less trauma for their families.
p150
aa(lp151
VFamilies can struggle with those conversations,
p152
aVbut for us, we also found that information immensely helpful with big decisions.
p153
aVMost notably,
p154
aVwhether to have a baby.
p155
aVMonths to a few years meant Paul was not likely to see her grow up.
p156
aVBut he had a good chance of being there for her birth
p157
aVand for the beginning of her life.
p158
aVI remember asking Paul
p159
aVif he thought having to say goodbye to a child
p160
aVwould make dying even more painful.
p161
aVAnd his answer astounded me.
p162
aVHe said,
p163
aV"Wouldn't it be great if it did?"
p164
aVAnd we did it.
p165
aVNot in order to spite cancer,
p166
aVbut because we were learning
p167
aVthat living fully means accepting suffering.
p168
aa(lp169
VPaul's oncologist tailored his chemo
p170
aVso he could continue working as a neurosurgeon,
p171
aVwhich initially we thought was totally impossible.
p172
aVWhen the cancer advanced
p173
aVand Paul shifted from surgery to writing,
p174
aVhis palliative care doctor prescribed a stimulant medication
p175
aVso he could be more focused.
p176
aVThey asked Paul about his priorities and his worries.
p177
aVThey asked him what trade-offs he was willing to make.
p178
aVThose conversations are the best way to ensure
p179
aVthat your health care matches your values.
p180
aVPaul joked that it's not like that "birds and bees" talk
p181
aVyou have with your parents,
p182
aVwhere you all get it over with as quickly as possible,
p183
aVand then pretend it never happened.
p184
aVYou revisit the conversation as things change.
p185
aVYou keep saying things out loud.
p186
aVI'm forever grateful
p187
aVbecause Paul's clinicians felt
p188
aVthat their job wasn't to try to give us answers they didn't have,
p189
aVor only to try to fix things for us,
p190
aVbut to counsel Paul through painful choices ...
p191
aVwhen his body was failing but his will to live wasn't.
