VA few weeks ago, a patient came into my clinic.
p202
aVA woman dealing with a serious chronic disease.
p203
aVAnd while we were talking about her life and her health care,
p204
aVshe said, "I love my palliative care team.
p205
aVThey taught me that it's OK to say 'no'."
p206
aVYeah, I thought, of course it is.
p207
aVBut many patients don't feel that.
p208
aVCompassion and Choices did a study
p209
aVwhere they asked people about their health care preferences.
p210
aVAnd a lot of people started their answers with the words
p211
aV"Well, if I had a choice ..."
p212
aVIf I had a choice.
p213
aVAnd when I read that "if,"
p214
aVI understood better
p215
aVwhy one in four people
p216
aVreceives excessive or unwanted medical treatment,
p217
aVor watches a family member receive excessive or unwanted medical treatment.
p218
aVIt's not because doctors don't get it.
p219
aVWe do.
p220
aVWe understand the real psychological consequences
p221
aVon patients and their families.
p222
aVThe things is, we deal with them, too.
p223
aVHalf of critical care nurses and a quarter of ICU doctors
p224
aVhave considered quitting their jobs
p225
aVbecause of distress over feeling that for some of their patients,
p226
aVthey've provided care that didn't fit with the person's values.
